<response>None< /response><gmapID>0x80dcd405ae7f8063:0xfb5909958973f843</gmapID>< Review>
I believe this location is a matter of necessity/convenience for many folks, like myself. Unfortunately, I need to rent from this location occasionally.  My experiences have never been great, or too bad, until recently.

I had rented a vehicle prior to this visit, and provided a review (to Hertz) of my experience. The vehicle I was given, was not clean, despite having waited 30 minutes for a wash.

I bring this up, because I received call from the branch manager, shortly after submitting my review. Hertz offers an option if you do not want to be contacted regarding you review; I made that selection. Despite this, the branch manager called me and let me know she was not pleased with my review. Really?!?!

I recently had to go back to rent another vehicle. When I arrived, there was a customer who was clearly frustrated.  He needed a sepcific vehicle and when the branch manager arrived, she barely acknowledged him.

I asked if I could rent 2 different vehicles on the lot, per the usual, I was told no. Last time it was because the vehicle I wanted needed an oil change that would take "8 hours". This time, it was because both vehicles were "reserved". I have rented from this location over a half a dozen times, and have never been given the vehicle I ask for. Based on my observations of other renters, this seems to be an issue for other patrons who visit this branch.

Getting back to this rental experience, I was given a very small SUV, that was absolutely disgusting on the inside. Considering the experience I just had with the branch manager, I had expected some effort would be put into making sure I was given a clean vehicle. Nope! Despite Covid, I was given a filthy vehicle, with unknown dried liquids splattered throughout. Also had very visible shoe marks all over the seats (please see photos).

If you do not need to rent from this location, I strongly suggest going to another branch, or other car rental company.</Review>

<UserId.>113359630557683292121<//UserId.>< review>
Every neighborhood needs a good greasy spoon.  This happens to be the spoon my girlfriend has gone for years and I understand why.  Friendly, happy staff, good food, and nothing fancy.  It's homey and I always feel comfortable.  Even our celebrity neighbors come here from time to time!

When I have a craving for pancakes the way my granny made, I go to Hilda's.  When I crave a good hangover cure or diner coffee and don't want to cook, Hilda's is there for us.</review>

1354481535079< /Time>
<rate>5</rate>< review>
My cousin took me to Hilda's to eat when I was visiting several years ago. The place felt very much like a restaurant back in my hometown. Very homey, very comfortable, a place where everyone knows your name. The food was out of this world, plenty of it and very reasonably priced. The service is great. The waitresses always have something to say, they recommend what they think you might like and they are always smiling.  It feels like extended family. Wish we had a similar place where I live now in Erie. Hope Hilda's is around for a long, long, long, long time.< /review>

<Text>Stumbled across Hilda's on a recent drive to San Anselmo. This place is about as mom and pop as they come. I almost ordered French toast but our very kindly waitress talked me into the pancakes, which I was assured Hilda's was famous for.

She wasn't kidding. These were seriously the best pancakes I've ever had in my life. Deliciously soft in the middle and then taking on a crispy crepe-like consistency as you approach the perimeter.

The whole experience makes this place worth a repeat morning breakfast visit to San Anselmo.< /Text><Pics>None</Pics>< resp>

< UserId.>
104179591958945331528<//UserId.>
<Name>Jordan Burchette</Name><date>1597427303885</date><Rating>5</Rating><text>What's great about comic book shops is that there's no franchise template; each is a unique little snowflake. There are things you expect, but each proprietor has a different take on them. The Comic Bug sells new issues, back issues, games, toys and collected editions and presents them in a way that engenders the feeling of discovery that makes a great comic book shop.

There's the huge wall of new and recent issues, which leads you to a robust selection of back issues, which leads you to the store's signature bin of issue runs -- sequential comics packaged up in story lots at a fair discount. Further, their sales are fantastic, clearing out discounted back issues, graphic novels and other items at serious reductions. A hundred dollars might not be a lot for some people to spend in a single purchase, but it is for me and I came out of that place with probably $200 worth of merchandise.

Atop it all, the folks running it are delightful; engaging customers, offering sincere help and running in-store promotions that foster a fun, communal vibe. I wish I lived closer, because The Comic Bug is a textbook example of the classic comic book store.<//text><pictures>None< /pictures>< resp>
None< /resp>

< Review>
I have buying my comics from here since I moved to Los Angeles in 2012. The staff is knowledgeable on the topic of comics. They are friendly, sociable, and carry a great conversation on most things comics. They know their repeat customers by name and comic preferences. If you are lucky, you might see people from the nearby movie studios show up. Also, they have connections to special movie screenings of select superheroes.  Also, if there is a comic book you want, but they do not carry, they can get.  This was helpful when I was looking for Voltron and Robotech. The place has wall-to-wall comics, merchandise, and limited edition items for your taste. Worth the visit and money.<//Review>

1621101025582</Time>
<rating>5<//rating>< review>
For those of you waiting until it is safe to get your dental work done. NOW is the time and THIS is definitely THE PLACE! (And, why can I only give 5 stars?!?!?!)    :)
Not only is the entire team 100% qualified, friendly, & helpful, but, they are also 100% committed to making each visit the best, most painless, & SAFEST dental visit EVER!
They've got the "covid protocols" down pat. From the second you walk in the door (spacing & plexiglass guards & face masks, etc.) through the treatment too (air purifiers, full protective gear, hand sanitizers, mouth rinse, etc.).
I had an emergency root canal in Jan (prior to me getting the vaccine) and they went out of their way to make sure I not only felt safe but WAS safe! I went back for my cleaning after I got my vaccine in April. And, now, I've gotten a failing crown fixed in May.
Seriously, if it is time (or past time) to get your dental work done, DO IT. Don't forget that healthy teeth help make a healthy you too.
This is the dental practice I've gone to since moving to CA. I've lived in four other states. This practice is the most up-to-date with the best techniques of ANY I've been to. And, to keep improving during the pandemic??? OUTSTANDING!!!!! (Can you tell I think very highly of them all?)  :)<//review>

< Review>
The bean dip is worth the price of admission!

I hadn‚Äôt been here in a while, and the whole experience was OK. To be fair, it was a busy Saturday night, and being recently reopened was definitely a challenge, so I think they did their best. The staff was very nice and the bean dip was as awesome as I remember. The food? So-so. I think mine was sitting in the window for a while because the enchilada sauce looked dry and crusty on the side, the once melted cheese had solidified, and the beans were sort of crusty and dried out. The enchilada was also dry - the taco was good, though! And again, the bean dip and the salsa were amazing. I‚Äôd still go back, but I hope the kitchen gets itself in order so the experience can be more pleasant. And again, the staff were very nice and accommodating.<//Review>

They said since we were a big party we could sit together but we had to sit outdoor. <Response>None</Response><user>108963239493502068437</user><Name>Don Schaffer</Name>< Text>
Los Toros has several different experiences under one roof including a dining floor that feels like an open-air market, an energetic bar with TVs playing current sports matchups, a quaint area decorated like cottage interiors, and a back room for larger groups.

The food is of high quality with decent portions and very reasonable prices, and they are willing to prepare meals for those who may have food allergies (gluten-free, in our case), though the menu doesn't currently note it. We have never been disappointed with service or the food.

Parking is likely the largest challenge, as Los Toros retains a steady yet manageable stream of guests. Valet is available, and there is ample street parking immediately nearby.

With all to like, it's easy to see why Los Toros is a community favorite with a draw from the rest of Los Angeles.< /Text>

< Rating>
4<//Rating>
< text>
Since the weekends here generate a brunch menu (not the normal lunch menu), we chose a pork based dish w/eggs. She had the Huevos Rancheros and I had the Sopa carnitas. We also had guacamole (best I've ever had) and some extra (fresh) tortillas. Food was delish. This is not  a typical Mexican restaurant (that overfeed you). It is a gourmet Mexican/American food place. The food was very skillfully cooked, excellently prepared and meticulously served. And the food was very reasonably priced too (total bill for 2, without drinks was about $60. We also had iced-tea, which was also very good (non fru-fru, just plain unflavored/unsweetened).< /text>

Parking during the day usually has valet and can be challenging in the evenings especially Friday or Saturday night. I recommend taking an uber/lyft here if possible, or carpooling. Otherwise you will likely have to park in the residential area. This is the type of place you go to for the atmosphere and the memories (aka drinking margaritas with your friends). The food is not amazing but it's not bad either. I recommend coming here for drinks and supplementing that with their food :). It can get really loud here (again because there is lots of margarita drinking happening here). < review>
Huge menu, excellent margarita choices (and decently priced). Call ahead for seating or plan to wait, because this is one of the more popular places to eat in the Valley, and wait times for seating (especially on weekends) can be long. The bean dip is excellent.< /review>

<rating>4</rating>< Text>
Can a menu have too many items on it? Los Toros says, NO! Literally hundreds maybe a thousand or so items on a very thick binder menu. The food is always tasty and the price is right. The waiters weren't just good they were enthusiastic! They got a big tip from us. My one star off is that the room where we were sat was too dark. Very hard to see the menu or anything. We had our phones out with the flashlights on. Dim is one thing but this was a level below that.< /Text>

<date>1576685921347</date><Text>I've been going to Los Toro's my entire life. I always get the same thing. Carne asada with an enchilada. It's always good, and always tastes exactly the same. That is until last night. I always defend Los Toro's when people say, it's gotten worse over the years, but I can no longer defend it. I ate in the bar, which might've been my first mistake. I had to stare at every employee just to get service. The bean dip, which they're famous for, was thick, not very hot, and given in A VERY small bowl. The carne asada was overcooked to well done, even though I asked for medium rare. I asked for no rice all beans, got a tiny bit of beans with and like a pound of rice. Then the enchilada wasn't even hot enough to melt the cheese on the inside or on top. Very sad. I'll go back to give them one more try, but maybe my friends are right and there is no defending them anymore.<//Text>< pics>

The drinks are always amazing and the bean dip they give you with the chips and salsa is absolutely addicting. However, I know that when we come to this place that the service is inconsistent and it's not always clean. The food is always on point but there are times when we wait a long time to get seated, the waiters are not attentive even when it appears that there are plenty of tables open. This last visit, the server was great and we were seated immediately but the bathrooms needed cleaning and the bar areas were messy. I give it a three due to the inconsistency between visits but if they're able to work that out, I'd give them 4-5 stars.</review>

<Rating>1<//Rating><Text>What a rip-off! I ordered the pescado asado, which was a small piece of swordfish with a dismal salad and terrible rice, and the way they served me was a huge disappointment...

The bloodline was still on the fish! The bloodline is not edible and as it was small, and for $17.95, it was hardly anything to eat! And the so-called salad that was included, was basically two pieces of iceberg lettuce with ONE slice of tomato.

My son had the beef flautas, and at first, they seemed huge but as he ate them, they were dry and the "little bit of" beef it had, was only in the openings at the top and at the bottom.

My husband had the carne asada plate and he was ok with the steak, but the rest of his plate was not  good... He had the chile relleno and the chile itself was a bit on the bitter side??

The rice was not great, it was 'off' in taste, and the pinto beans were from cannned beans and not fresh tasting, with way too much cheese over it, (where were the beans???)...

I complained to the waitress about my swordfish plate, and I saw her talk to the manager, who was younger than her, and he seemed unconcerned and careless, and he didn't even bother to apologize about the swordfish, which was the only thing I complained about to her...

It really wasn't her fault, but the idiotic manager on duty, in his immaturity should at least have approached us. I guess he figured his restaurant was top quality, and we were too insignificant to acknowledge.

Bottom-line: The food is not quality, you might get quantity but not great authentic food. Don't waste your money here, instead go to a true Mexican food place in Reseda... Las Fuentes... Now that's good food! And not expensive and super-authentic!

I don't understand why or how people gave this location any good reviews! I honestly went by the reviews and I was extremely disappointed at the end... Maybe most of them go there for quantity, and for sure you will get that... But ask yourself, why stuff yourself with high fat, low quality? I would rather have smaller portions and with quality!

<text>What a rip-off! I ordered the pescado asado, which was a small piece of swordfish with a dismal salad and terrible rice, and the way they served me was a huge disappointment...

The bloodline was still on the fish! The bloodline is not edible and as it was small, and for $17.95, it was hardly anything to eat! And the so-called salad that was included, was basically two pieces of iceberg lettuce with ONE slice of tomato.

My son had the beef flautas, and at first, they seemed huge but as he ate them, they were dry and the "little bit of" beef it had, was only in the openings at the top and at the bottom.

My husband had the carne asada plate and he was ok with the steak, but the rest of his plate was not  good... He had the chile relleno and the chile itself was a bit on the bitter side??

The rice was not great, it was 'off' in taste, and the pinto beans were from cannned beans and not fresh tasting, with way too much cheese over it, (where were the beans???)...

I complained to the waitress about my swordfish plate, and I saw her talk to the manager, who was younger than her, and he seemed unconcerned and careless, and he didn't even bother to apologize about the swordfish, which was the only thing I complained about to her...

It really wasn't her fault, but the idiotic manager on duty, in his immaturity should at least have approached us. I guess he figured his restaurant was top quality, and we were too insignificant to acknowledge.

Bottom-line: The food is not quality, you might get quantity but not great authentic food. Don't waste your money here, instead go to a true Mexican food place in Reseda... Las Fuentes... Now that's good food! And not expensive and super-authentic!

I don't understand why or how people gave this location any good reviews! I honestly went by the reviews and I was extremely disappointed at the end... Maybe most of them go there for quantity, and for sure you will get that... But ask yourself, why stuff yourself with high fat, low quality? I would rather have smaller portions and with quality!

So think about it and be aware!</text>< Pics>

< text>
I came for lunch and ordered the Cilantro Ceasar chicken salad, I have to say, it was just ok.  The lettuce was chopped badly, there was way to much of the core in the salad.....and it looked old as well.  The chicken was decent, but a bit dry.  The dressing was really good, but nothing "ceasar" about it.  Overall, I would not order it again.  Although, I must say, the chips, salsa and bean dip were very good.
The staff was friendly, but it seemed like they'd rather be somewhere else.  I look forward to one day returning to try something else, some of the other plates I saw looked good.  Anyhow, this was just my observations on this visit.</text>

1551332028493<//Time>
< Rating>
1</Rating>
< text>
This place is dangerous.  Avoid!

For years I came to this restaurant with my children little did I know it had become a place of violence.  Last Cinco de Mayo 2018 I was there with my family for dinner and was attacked by 3 men inside the restaurant.  I was beaten, stomped on and dragged through broken  glass.

I am a woman in my 50s and was there to have a family dinner.   Imagine your mom being beat up by 3 men in a family restaurant!

Despite a number of security guards on duty no one was there to help me when these people became unruly.  I asked that 911 be called and the men who attacked me be arrestested.  The owner's allowed the men and 2 women to just walk away.

Though the restaurant had credit card receipts and video cameras all around, some how they were unable to assist police in identifying these violent criminals.  I was told by bus boy that one of the women was a regular and well known there.

Later the LAPD detective assigned to my case told me officers had been called there many times in the last year.  In fact there are other accounts on Yelp describing acts of violence at this establishment including one of a women being choked by some deranged man who wandered in.   According to that account restaurant security did not act at all and other diners had to subdue the man and get his bely from around the woman"s throat.  The diners detained him until LAPD arrived.  In my case management, it was told to me that security and management encouraged them to leave before police arrived.

As a consequence of my injuries I had to be taken to the ER for medical treatment and now have a big ugly scar on my leg.

It was a very traumatic experience made worse by the restaurant's unsympathetic and unhelpful attitude.

I would avoid this place.  Please DO NOT take your children here.

It is not safe.  Absolutely NOT SAFE.

Los Toros if you would like to challenge this review, I would be happy to post the police report. As well as the call sheet I obtained from LAPD detailing all the 911 runs made to your establishment in 2018.< /text>

< Review>
One of the best places in the Valley to get authentic Mexican food. I've been going here for decades and the food is always excellent. The bean dip is good, the salsa is tasty, the machaca is very good. They've got great chimichangas, they've got excellent tamales, they even have a point to Vallarta shrimp cocktail which is more soupy than like your traditional shrimp cocktail. Even the chips are freshly made every day. Plus there Margarita will knock you out so be careful and only have one or two.</Review>

< text>
One of the best places in the Valley to get authentic Mexican food. I've been going here for decades and the food is always excellent. The bean dip is good, the salsa is tasty, the machaca is very good. They've got great chimichangas, they've got excellent tamales, they even have a point to Vallarta shrimp cocktail which is more soupy than like your traditional shrimp cocktail. Even the chips are freshly made every day. Plus there Margarita will knock you out so be careful and only have one or two.< /text>

I suggested to my friend we go the Los Toros for dinner tonight. I was excited to share a favorite restaurant with a friend. Was ensued was one of the most terrifying experiences ever. As we sat waiting for our server, the couple next to us, the man appeared to become very agitated. He kept making political references to President Trump very loudly and was obviously agitated by us. He kept looking over at us stabbing his food and making racial comments. We tried to ignore him but he escalated his attacks calling us white trash. He repeated screamed at us threats and that he f-ing hates all white people. Then he said he was a former Marine and that gave him the right to say whatever he wanted. Then he said he'd been in "the pen" for 26 years so we should f-ing leave. His repeated claim of hating white people prompted someone to ask him to leave. He was screaming that we said bad things about Mexicans. We never did. Besides if we hated Mexicans why would we go to one of the oldest and most famous Mexican restaraunts in Los Angeles? His rant continued. I asked for the manager. She finally came over and ushered him out telling him he should go before we (my friend and I) call the police. <name>Hoa Slezak<//name><Date>1410821119171</Date><rating>4</rating><text>I definitely love the atmosphere.  The murals and lighting really set the mood. I've been here for lunch, brunch, and dinner. Portions are more than enough. Most recently, I have been the Sunday Brunch, $17.95/person with your choice of champagne, mimosas, or margaritas. Regarding drinks, you can't change it up mid-meal. So if you ordered a mimosa, you had to have refills of mimosa. Our party ordered the mimosas. The drinks started off nicely, evenly balanced. But each time we were given a refill, our drinks tasted more and more like straight oj. I was not blown away with most of the food offered at the brunch, sadly. <name>Richard Basil<//name><Date>1496252409329</Date>< Rate>
5</Rate>
< Review>
Homestyle Mexican food from a great, family-run restaurant.  The new phone boo..I mean Gigantic Menu Books may be hard for we senior citizens to navigate, or even to heft upward as we seek the familiar list of "Bulls":  a long-running set of excellent combination or specialty plates including pork medallions ("Alambres Mexicanos") and el ultimo mas fino, "Aaron's" the 9th Bull.  The margaritas are generous, the chips are fresh and salted, the salsa is excellent (ask for the rare picante batch) and the bean dip is a justified legend dampened only by serving containers far too parsimonious to meet the needs of Montano family customers who actually ask to sit in the "old section" because it reminds us of a time when the food was exactly as good, the service was exactly as friendly, there were horses hitched out back and the current owner was just a cute kid working for his dad.  This is great, old Los Angeles style Mexican food and there's no place better for a fun, relaxing, excellent meal.   Now, how do I convince Nick to allow me to bring my own bowl for the bean dip?</Review>

5< /rate>
<text>Homestyle Mexican food from a great, family-run restaurant.  The new phone boo..I mean Gigantic Menu Books may be hard for we senior citizens to navigate, or even to heft upward as we seek the familiar list of "Bulls":  a long-running set of excellent combination or specialty plates including pork medallions ("Alambres Mexicanos") and el ultimo mas fino, "Aaron's" the 9th Bull.  The margaritas are generous, the chips are fresh and salted, the salsa is excellent (ask for the rare picante batch) and the bean dip is a justified legend dampened only by serving containers far too parsimonious to meet the needs of Montano family customers who actually ask to sit in the "old section" because it reminds us of a time when the food was exactly as good, the service was exactly as friendly, there were horses hitched out back and the current owner was just a cute kid working for his dad.  This is great, old Los Angeles style Mexican food and there's no place better for a fun, relaxing, excellent meal.   Now, how do I convince Nick to allow me to bring my own bowl for the bean dip?< /text>< Pics>
None</Pics>

<userid>112941743792993086771</userid><username>Jordan Slezak<//username><Date>1447386054819</Date>< Rating>
5</Rating>
<Text>Come hungry because Los Toros portion sizes are very filling. Doesn't matter if you order food for breakfast, lunch or dinner... your going to get a lot of food on your plate! And speaking of filling, they have some awesome (free) bean dip *you can ask for vegetarian friendly bean dip fyi*( which is freakkkkking amazing!), salsa and chips to munch on while you wait for your food to arrive.

You have 3 places to choose from to sit which are: at the bar, on the patio or in a large section inside (fully covered room). They have a full bar and they have many Mexican types of beers on tap (I like Corona and Modelo the best!) Speaking of drinks their house margarita on the rocks is pretty bomb!I really liked the veggie burrito plate (Comes with Mexican rice and beans) and I loaded it up with their salsa. So good!

*Other important information: They have Sunday brunch from 10am to 3pm (Haven't been to it yet, but I heard about it from the bartender, when I asked about Happy Hour specials.) During the brunch you can do bottomless mimosas, which sounds veryyyyyyyy inviting in my book. Happy hour is from 3pm to 7pm, but not fully sure what days. But they seem to have daily specials of something everyday, even on the weekends. Parking is pretty awesome... FINALLY I find a parking lot that's decently sized for a large restaurant!

Off the 118 Freeway and not too far from the 101 Freeway if your looking for a place to steer away from the traffic madness and grab some grub and have a cold beer!<//Text>< pics>
